G√∂khan Arer is a photographer based in Istanbul who finds clever ways to reveal hidden scenes in everyday life. His work is playful, often capturing humorous juxtapositions that spotlight moments most people would overlook.

To get these shots, he keeps his camera settings ready and uses zone focusing, allowing him to react quickly and concentrate entirely on framing, without losing time.

His goal is simple, to make people feel good and, hopefully, make them smile.

caption:
‚ÄúCollecting Hands is an ongoing photo series that focuses on the details and textures of the human hand. With each set of hands, comes a unique story of one‚Äôs life ‚Äî our accomplishments, struggles, hard work, and sacrifices. 
Many of these stories can be told by the varying nuances in clothing, skin tones, and even the items the subject holds. In piecing together this series, I‚Äôm reminded of the simple beauty of humanity within these frames. This series is a grounding prompt that no pair of hands share or tell the same story, yet somehow, despite our different experiences in life, we‚Äôre able to relate to one another on one common ground: 
Life.‚Äù - Sony #AlphaCollective member @monaris_ ü§ù

Shot with Sony Alpha 1 + 35mm F1.4 G Master + 24-70mm F2.8 G Master II. #SonyAlpha

caption:
We have to be always ready for Candid moments to shoot cause photography will never warn you about the opportunities that it will give to us. This photo has been taken on the way back home. I always have my camera with me and I have seen the frame, took out my camera and shot it, it is for sure that the time to shoot was not more than 10 seconds and it will not wait for you to shoot. Please open your eyes like a radar and try to see what is going around. To look is not enough to shoot, you have to see it and you have to be ready for shooting.

What is your opinion?

‚ÄúHo 54 anni e sono di Istanbul.
Sposato e padre di un figlio di 21 anni. Sono un ingegnere chimico e ho una piccola azienda che si occupa di gomma e silicone!
Ho iniziato a scattare fotografie nel 2015 e fin da subito mi concentrato sulla fotografia di strada per creare giustapposizioni. 
Ero imembro del Turkuaz Street Collective e sono il fondatore delCollettivo di Istanbul Candid Street Photography @istanbulcandidstreet 
Cerco di stare per strada spesso per cercare i momenti sorprendenti della vita quotidiana che generalmente non vediamo e notiamo attraverso il flusso costante di persone che si muovono nelle citt√†. Mi piace osservare ci√≤ che mi ho intorno e cercare di trovare scene illusorie. 
Di solito le persone sono il fulcro delle mie foto.
Assistere alle sorprese della vita e immortalare quelle scene √® la parte pi√π preziosa e piacevole della mia passione!
Per me la Street Photography √® come un antidepressivo che apre un cancello speciale per un mondo meraviglioso attraverso il pulsante dell‚Äôotturatore‚Äù

caption:
Yesterday there was a protest in Kadikoy against Animal's Law (which will be a disaster for stray animals starting with the dogs). 

I was there as an animal lover and took some shots. Speaking honestly, under the emotional mood when you empathize about what these animals will face after the new law, it is not easy to shoot. 

Here is one of the photos i took yesterday. I wanted to make a juxtaposition to express the mood of the people there. 

As we say "Istanbul is a Paradise for Street photography" but sometimes it may turn into hell. 

Please cancel the Animals law or reform it to give a chance for stray animals to live in their neighborhood.

As a passionate of Candid Street Photography, I am after the surprising moments in daily life which we generally don't see and notice through the flow. I like to observe what is going around me and try to find illusion-like scenes which we rarely see. 

People are usually at the center of my photos. Witnessing the surprises in life and immortalizing those scenes is the most valuable and enjoyable part of my passion. 
For me, Street Photography is like an anti-depressant which opens a special gate to a wonderful world through the shutter button.

Recap of our trip to Japan üáØüáµ

Well - that‚Äôs a wrap on our trip to Japan! üôå

We had SUCH an incredible time. The food, people, culture, hospitality‚Ä¶ everything was amazing and we both can‚Äôt wait to go back

‚Äî

üìñ Quick Backstory

So‚Ä¶ why did we go to Japan in the first place? 

We both do stranger portraits in North America, but we were told it would be SUPER difficult to do a project like this in Japan, due to the language and cultural differences.

So we wanted to see if we could overcome these challenges and use photography to capture unique, memorable portraits of the people of Japan.

We believe that art & photography can connect people on a fundamental level. One that transcends borders, languages and cultural norms. 

So when @adorama heard about this idea - they wanted to help us make it a reality.

They hooked us up with gear from @polarpro, @loweprobags, @sandiskprofessional, @jobyinc, @djiglobal & @tiffencompany to help make shooting & offloading a breeze. And we filmed all the BTS/updates on the DJI Osmo Pocket 3‚Äôs from @osmo_global. 

We also got to visit @sony HQ and meet the team. Big shout out to the folks at @sonyalpha & @sony_jp for their incredible hospitality!

This trip wouldn‚Äôt have been possible without @adorama, and we‚Äôre super proud to partner with brands who believe in using art as a way to connect with people all over the world. üôè

‚Äî

‚úàÔ∏è Where to next? 

We‚Äôre planning our next trip for 2025 - where should we visit next? Drop your suggestions in the comments üëá

‚Äú‚ÄòPainterly Thoughts' was captured from the backseat of a taxi in Kolkata on a rainy day.  As the city moved past me, the glass turned into a canvas‚Äîwarping colors, distorting figures, and blending reality into something almost surreal. What first caught my attention was the man‚Äôs intense gaze in the rearview mirror, a quiet contrast to the chaotic scene outside. The rain, the reflections, the movement. Everything merged into a fleeting composition that felt more like a painting than a photograph. This image is about that in-between space, where everyday moments become something more, shaped by light, texture, and time.‚Äù

caption:
Street portrait photography in Hong Kong captures the essence of a city that is both bustling and deeply cultural. 

The Leica Q3, with its versatility and the possibility of using it in hyperfocal distance, is the perfect tool for street photography. 

But for street portraits, the Leica SL3 paired with a 50mm Summilux M lens offers unparalleled quality. The combination of the SL3's exceptional image sensor and the Summilux's legendary sharpness and bokeh allows for stunning portraiture.

Photographing the streets and people of Hong Kong with the right equipment not only enhances your technical capabilities but also deepens your connection with this vibrant metropolis. The Leica Q3 and SL3, with their exceptional performance, allow you to capture the true essence of Hong Kong, one portrait at a time.

Directed by @lorenzorazzino

caption:
Taking street photos in Hong Kong at night with the Q3 and its ultra-bright lens is exceptional. The city's vibrant streets, illuminated by neon signs, offer stunning photo opportunities.

The Q3's low-light performance and sharp lens capture the vibrant scenes with incredible clarity. Its fast aperture creates impressive depth of field, making subjects stand out. Compact and ergonomic, the Q3 is perfect for maneuvering through crowds and capturing the essence of Hong Kong's nightlife.

Each shot tells a vivid story of this dynamic city.

Directed by @lorenzorazzino

caption:
I love taking street photography in Hong Kong because the city is a constant source of inspiration. The vibrant streets, neon lights, bustling markets, and diverse crowds provide endless captivating shots. With my Q3 for wide-context shots and the M11 with a 50mm Summilux for street portraits, I capture the unique contrast between modern skyscrapers and traditional temples. The Leica lenses deliver stunning black-and-white images with remarkable contrast and detail. Both cameras perform exceptionally well in challenging conditions, such as Hong Kong's rain and humidity. The dynamic energy and rich culture make Hong Kong a wonderful city for street photography, always offering new and exciting moments to capture.

Directed by @lorenzorazzino

Hong Kong is a vibrant city, perfect for street photography. Using the Leica Q3 with its 28mm lens and the Leica M11 with the 50mm Summilux lens, you can capture the essence of its people.

The 28mm lens on the Q3 allows for wide-angle shots that include both people and their surroundings, ideal for environmental portraits in markets, alleys, and neon-lit streets.

The 50mm Summilux on the M11 is great for intimate portraits, offering a natural perspective and beautiful bokeh, perfect for capturing emotions and expressions.

Hong Kong‚Äôs diverse population offers a wealth of unique stories. Approach your subjects with respect, and engage with them for the best portraits. The combination of these lenses will help you create stunning images that reflect the spirit of Hong Kong.

Directed by @lorenzorazzino

Hong Kong epitomizes dynamism with its bustling markets filled with aromas, the sound of rain, and its efficient urban infrastructure. The markets offer a vibrant mix of goods and cultural experiences, while districts like Central and Tsim Sha Tsui showcase towering skyscrapers and cutting-edge technology.

Connecting these diverse areas is Hong Kong's highly efficient metro system, renowned for its punctuality and convenience. The Q3 is the perfect tool to capture this speed and movement. With its advanced features, it provides precise shots that reflect the dynamic spirit of Hong Kong, from the aromas of the markets to the sound of rain, the metro sounds to a grandfather playing with his grandson on a city basketball court.

Directed by @lorenzorazzino

caption:
GUEST CURATOR SELECTION

Hello everyone, today is once again the moment to celebrate the fantastic connection between @streetphotographybrazil and @street_avengers . To that end, we are presenting a selection of works by Alexandre Coelho Lima ( @alexcoelholima ), a Portuguese photographer whose perspective is shaped by his architectural training. Switching between black&white and color, his images always demonstrate a clear preference for geometry and storytelling through solitary human presence. His search for the interplay of light and shadow, shows his aim to polighteness by eliminating visual noise and leading our eyes to the stories themselves.

Hello everyone! This is Amelia Sagone Rattew from @rroma.street. It's a great pleasure to be here in partnership with @streetphotographybrazil to present the beautiful work of Jason Buckley. @jason__buckley is a British photographer based in London, UK. Jason is unafraid to explore, experiment, and push the boundaries of street photography, thus creating images that are ambiguous, graphically powerful, mesmerizing, and just beautiful. His work draws us into unexpected scenes, offering a mix of quiet poetry and surreal atmosphere. Congratulations, Jason! I hope you all enjoy his outstanding work. Here is Marcelo, from @streetphotographybrazil It is a great pleasure to be here, in partnership with @rroma.street to present you the beautiful and thought-provoking work of photographer @s_o_f_ Her fotos make us image the most varied scenarios, combining sophistication, minimalist beauty, sense of humor and sensuality. The constant presence of the artist‚Äôs own silhouette in the pictures is an intriguing and distinctive touch, and an invitation to dive into her profound and at the same time simple artistic expression. Congratulations Sophie, for the wonderful set of images! Hope you all enjoy her outstanding work! caption:
Want to learn the elements of what make a great street photograph?

üíÉüèª Join me on a weekend adventure exploring Malaga in Spain with like-minded photographers. We'll be there during Holy Week AKA Semana Santa chasing pointy hats as well as photographing the city!

I'll teach you as much as I can fit in and set you challenging yet achievable street photography assignments adaptable to your level of experience. You'll also get a sightseeing itinerary and fun group meals making the whole experience awesome!

YOU LEARN
üì∏  How to set yourself up for success with the right mindset
üì∏  Ways of "working the scene"
üì∏  How to read the street and think like a street photographer
üì∏  How to "make something out of nothing"
üì∏  The keys to ambiguity and mystery
üì∏  Dos and don'ts of framing and cropping
üì∏  Things to look out for to create context and connections
üì∏  How to tell a story (or multiple stories) with a single shot
üì∏  The blueprint for a great photo
üì∏  An introduction to the gestalt principles of visual perception
üì∏  How to approach crowded places in multiple creative ways
üì∏  What to avoid and keep an eye on when shooting
üì∏  Ways to structure your images compositionally
üì∏  And more...

I don't hold anything back, and if you join a Weekender with an event I'll teach you how to shoot events like a street photographer not an event photographer!

Featured photographers in this post showcasing work from previous Seville workshops:
@bb.streetphoto
@nookiedog 
@stephen.today
@bruno.ccc
@kackaska
@johnpaulpierrot

MONTHLY THEME WINNERS Thank you to everyone who shared their SELF street photography! Mega apologies for the late posting of the winners - I was in Athens prepping for a hosting the Athens Weekender (which was awesome BTW!) Anyway, it was almost impossible to choose an overall winner because all the photos were so good and so different. You can see that you can create very creative street photos with yourself as the subject. Congratulations to all the winners especially to the overall winner: @latifebaudet And a shout out to @kackaska for making me laugh with her cone on the head shot every time I see it! Featured photographers: @latifebaudet üèÜ @emirssevim @instajlu @calleretratos @aledelu75 @mrmostarr @fotorenja @gonenasli @kackaska What I love about the winning image by @latifebaudet is the cinematic mood. There‚Äôs just enough light to pick up the facial features and that yellow daisy shape contrasts with the dark and rainy vibe! It made me think of film noir! Please go and check out @latifebaudet feed and show her some love‚Ä¶ *photos are not in any particular order except for the winner being the first shot obvs New THEME is coming in a couple of days! @m_h_raines here for my final day of the takeover. After moving back to Portland I decided to put down my film cameras and embrace all things digital. Something about the ease of the camera, the ability to be spontaneous without the costs associated with film, made it a tool that embraces playfulness and mistakism in a way that I really respond to at this moment in my life. I‚Äôm happy to unloosen my grip on control and allow the camera to do weird things for me. Here‚Äôs some recent digital stuff from the past several months. (jk) _________________________

@m_h_raines here again. I want to share the work of fellow Portland photographer @chrisnesseth . Chris and I have a similar sensibility and I loved the use of his flash and color. I‚Äôm almost certainly always going to run into Chris during one of my walks downtown and am constantly impressed by his dedication and all the hours he puts in. Chris also shoots for @willametteweek a local paper here in Portland and weekly he‚Äôs churning out solid pics. Go give him a follow if you haven‚Äôt already! üí™üí™ _________________________

caption:
Blake Andrews AKA @swerdnaekalb needs no introduction here but if you don‚Äôt know Blake, either by his images or his book reviews or his photo meet-ups or even his ‚ÄúPhotography is not a crime‚Äù bumper stickers, go ahead and do yourself a huge favor and familiarize yourself with all his work. I think I remember someone once saying that with the constant downpour of content now, curators will be play an essential role in our culture, on par with priests and politicians.  Blake certainly fits that role nicely in the photo community‚Ä¶in addition to being a great photographer. Check out his work if you haven‚Äôt already. Side note: He‚Äôs got a thoughtful write-up on Daniel Arnold‚Äôs Pickpocket at the Collector Daily site which is worth the read :)

MONTHLY THEME WINNERS Thank you to everyone who shared their LOVE street photography! I really enjoyed seeing the photos. Especially as we could do with more love in the world right now. So I hope you enjoy seeing the photos and feelin‚Äô the looooooove!!!! caption:
Welcome new followers, and hello existing followers. I appreciate you all! 

On this account I share street photography mostly featuring photos from people who have attended my workshops, but there‚Äôs also the monthly hashtag challenge, which is open to everyone! If you grab my free guide: "10 WAYS TO BECOME A FEARLESS STREET PHOTOGRAPHER plus my no#1 street photography hack‚Äù you‚Äôll be automatically subscribed to my email list and after an initial series of emails to help boost your street photography I‚Äôll send occasional newsletters.

A little bit about me‚Ä¶ I'm Polly @pollyrusynphoto and I‚Äôve been teaching street photography for around a decade. And I‚Äôve been a professional photographer during that time too shooting mainly personal brand photography, headshots (I‚Äôve shot over 600 people‚Äôs faces), and some events (the photos in this post are from Semana Santa in Malaga 2023, although this was not a commissioned shoot)! 

All of this is coming to an end though as a new chapter has started for me and I‚Äôve retrained as a coach and hypnotist (not available for parties haha cos I‚Äôm not that kind of hypnotist!). You can see my other account @pollyrusyn if you are curious. I love the work! In fact I don‚Äôt do anything I don‚Äôt love. And my love for street photography will not end I just simply can‚Äôt run two businesses and put my all into them both. 

So that‚Äôs why the weekend workshops I am hosting next year will be my last. I will miss doing them though! 

The best part of them is the community I‚Äôve built. Truly lovely people join me and I love them to bits. Many have become friends, even after they stop coming on the workshops (there‚Äôs only so many times you can hear my jokes haha!).

Anyway, the year is coming to a close, and I wish y‚Äôall all the very bestest of  the best. I love you. There I‚Äôve said it! Haha. May all your dreams come true in the year to come ‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®

caption:
ü§© Hello to the entire @streetphotographybrazil community, this is @soniasimbolo , streetphotographer and member of @street_avengers . 
üì∏ For our third monthly appointment, as guest curator, I decided to share the work of a photographer with exceptional sensitivity and talent: Fabio Moscatelli. @fabio74.moscatelli . The images you will see are part of his latest work ‚ÄúQui vive Jeeg‚Äù.
Good viewing to all ü•∞

‚ÄúI was born in Rome, where I currently live and work.
I graduated at the Roma School of Photography and Cinema and over the years I have specialised in social reporting and intimate storytelling, often focusing on people and stories at the margins of society.
Some of my published works are:
The Last Exit (2016);
Nostos (2020), a journey in my childhood done through revisiting the areas of central Italy affected by a major earthquake six years ago.
Gioele, il mondo fuori (2021), my latest publication, featuring Gioele, a  young boy on the autism spectrum, with whom I have been collaborating closely for the past few years.
Il Pranzo della domenica, a project dedicated to the memory of my paternal grandmother, was published in December 2022 while Animals, a publication dedicated to the animals in the earthquake-affected areas of Central Italy, is a 2023 posterzine. In 2025 I self published Qui Vive Jeeg, a book that tells the story of the suburb of Rome called Torbellamonaca.
Since 2019 I have been a lecturer at Officine Fotografiche and since 2024 the Artistic Director of the ETS Frame For Life, of which I am also a founder.
I have published in several national and international newspapers such as La Lettura del Corriere della Sera, Venerd√¨ di Repubblica and Mind
I organize courses and workshops dedicated to storytelling, with particular attention to photo editing.
My collaborations include a workshop with Magnum photographer Alec Soth and with Sam Harris, as well as several initiatives with national photographers.‚Äù

caption:
¬°Hola! @visualchaski here sharing a series of photographs I took in Coney Island last year. 

‚ÄúSudden storm, Coney Island, July 22nd, 2020‚Äù.

The usually crowded July beaches were already empty because of the pandemic. In a matter of 30 minutes, a heavy storm blew through creating a post-apocalyptic landscape for the few souls trying to escape to the beach.

Coney Island has been photographed endlessly, but the unusual sun shower showed a different face of the familiar summer playground of many New Yorkers.

caption:
@eleonoresimon again. In early 2020 I joined the collective @upphotographers, not quite knowing how a collective worked, but excited to find out! ‚Ä®‚Ä®In the group I found a great community of people to work with, exchange ideas and inspirations. They‚Äôve been a great support in many ways, and have been generous sharing experiences and advice as I was planning my first solo exhibition and had a ton of questions. So I‚Äôll say this: go out there and find your people! It doesn‚Äôt need to be a collective, but having people around whose eyes and opinions you trust is invaluable.

Which brings me to this: last year, the women of @upphotographers conducted free portfolio reviews for women and non-binary photographers to help them move their projects forward. We‚Äôre very excited to bring the reviews back and will announce the details soon on @upphotographers. Stay tuned!

This has been short and sweet! Thank you @ihatestreetphotography for the invitation to hang out on your feed these last few days. I will say my goodbyes with some pictures of Valpara√≠so with an ocean view.

In one of the very first edits of this project, I hadn‚Äôt included any pictures of the Pacific. A strange thing for a port city, and an interesting blind spot. With time, I started including more images with the ocean, and others that had a sense of openness. Perhaps simple whims of the editing process, perhaps a result of not finding myself as lost in the city as I once was. So cheers to finding your way, getting lost, and finding your way again, with a camera in hand. ‚Äî@eleonoresimon

caption:
Series by @fotorenja made on the Istanbul Masterclass Weekend 2024

üì∏ ‚ÄúGolden Horn Mosaic"

This was the first masterclass I have run after having run many many workshops. The format is very different to a Weekender, also you have to attended a Weekender to be able to join a Masterclass. 

The objective is to create a photo series so there is more preparation and individual research followed by autonomous shooting and intensive 1-1 and peer editing/selection sessions as series develop. 

The next Masterclass takes place in Rome 07-09 JUN 2025. And Rome really has it all for street photography - spectacular "stages", plenty of stories, and incredible light.

[Sat + Sun all-day, Mon PM PLUS 2-hr online workshop pre-masterclass]

Comment or DM me for more info about the Masterclass or about the Weekenders coming up next year or about 1-1 tuition!

Hello there! This is my irregular ‚ÄúWelcome New Followers‚Äù post. So great to have you here, I appreciate you for following and I hope you stick around. I share street photography mostly featuring photos from people who have attended my workshops, but there‚Äôs also the monthly hashtag challenge, which is open to everyone!

üìï Quick update on the new book I‚Äôm writing!

The words have had one set of eyeballs other than mine on them so far (by a Weekender participant). This is what they said:

"Absolutely loved it! I think it's fantastic. Easy to read and understand, great descriptions and easy to follow. I like how it's build up and how you included composition tips without listing them in an extra section. I also really like the "on xyz" chapters in between. It really covered a weekender. It was fun to read and curious about what comes next (even though I guessed it as I just have been on a weekender)."

I've selected the photographs (more or less) and will share some of the process in my IG stories - I may have shared some before you get this email so head to the highlights)

And I've updated my portfolio FINALLY! At least the portfolio bit - the collections still need updating. So if you would like a neck peek of some of the photos that will be in the book then head over there. (As I've already mentioned in my cheeky commercial break - my portfolio has been created in Format).

The book is essentially everything I teach on my street photography weekend workshops (which will be coming to an end, hence the book!), but more in-depth, and with musings on different topics to along with all my best photographs. 

Stay tuned. It's coming soon.
Speak soon ‚Äî Polly

p.s. I'm thinking of this photo for the cover. What do you think?

caption:
We need to talk... about photography!

Join a small friendly group in this very structured online chat. Everyone gets a voice! And you are guaranteed to walk away with plenty of takeaways to apply to your own work. 

PHOTO CHAT Saturday 16 November - 09:30-11:30 (GMT)

WHAT
This is a very structured online chat with a small yet perfectly formed group of people. We deconstruct the photography of the famous, debate the results of a photography competition, or get opinionated on other street photography matters! It's a bold move, but it's a lot of fun and there's a lot to be learned from spending time studying, discussing and evaluating the content and composition of images.

WHERE
GOOGLE MEET ONLINE

The link is emailed 48 hours before.

WHEN 
Saturday 16 November 09:30-11:30 (GMT)

HOW IT WORKS
The specific photographer (or topic) will be revealed a couple of days before along with your easy homework instructions. 

On the day we warm up with some chit chat.

I will introduce the photographer or topic we're discussing.

Everyone presents their homework with others in the group getting the opportunity to contribute insights (each photo only gets about 5-10 minutes so it's very easy)

You walk away inspired and enlightened!

SPACES ARE LIMITED (max 12, including your host) MINIMUM group of 3 needed for the Photo Chat to go ahead. [IMPORTANT: If for some reason this is not met I will either be in touch to reschedule or refund you the fee in full]

WHO‚ÄôS IN?!!
Me, me!!! And you?

Grab your spot now ‚Äî places are limited.

Comment the word CHAT and I'll DM you the link.

caption:
Photos by me @pollyrusyn

Hello there! This is my irregular ‚ÄúWelcome New Followers‚Äù post. So great to have you here, I appreciate you for following, and I hope you stick around. I share street photography mostly featuring photos from people who have attended my workshops, but there‚Äôs also the monthly hashtag challenge, which is open to everyone! If you grab my free guide: "10 WAYS TO BECOME A FEARLESS STREET PHOTOGRAPHER plus my no#1 street photography hack‚Äù you‚Äôll be automatically subscribed to my email list and I send newsletters now and again.

Here‚Äôs my street photography journey so far: 

üìå Found out the kind of photography I enjoyed most was called street photography
üìå Began doing street photography as a hobby and was shooting regularly at weekends
üìå Started a meet-up group teaching what I was learning and it grew quickly
üìå Won some awards, got published in magazines, took part in group exhibitions
üìå Founded the Department of Street Photography and started running workshops and creating resources and courses
üìå Became a Fujifilm Ambassador for 3 years!
üìå Gave talks at the Nat Geo Masterclasses and other events
üìå Judged some competitions and got featured in magazines
üìå Contributed to 3 books and wrote and published 2 of my own, and a zine (one of my books became an Amazon best-seller)
üìå Currently writing a NEW BOOK which is super exciting as well as challenging. So watch this space for news and updates (and defo get on my list because I‚Äôll have a special launch offer available to subscribers)

It‚Äôs been a wild ride! If I can do it anyone can, because I believe everything is learnable. And the way I teach is to break everything down into the elements of great photos and how to arrange them in your frame. 

I'd love to hear about your street photography goals, achievements, or things you‚Äôd like to learn about! Drop them into the comments or feel free to DM me.

Speak soon ‚Äî Polly

caption:
INSPIRATION - Alex Webb

All photos ¬© Alex Webb / Magnum Photos

Anyone who knows me knows that my biggest street photography inspiration is Alex Webb (or Lord Alex of Webb as I've taken to calling him haha). I had the pleasure of hearing him and his wife Rebecca Norris Webb give a talk several years ago in London. After the talk with a copy of their book 'Slant Rhymns' in my hand asked them for their autographs, and also asked Alex for his permission to intellectualise his work in a workshop I was running called "Through the Eyes of Alex Webb". He doesn't intellectualise what he does. He feels his way. He's a very intuitive photographer. And he gave me full permission! 

Anyway, one of my favourite books of his is 'Istanbul: A City of a Hundred Names' and the pictured you see here are from that wonderful and inspirational book. And it was also one of the reasons I chose Istanbul as the location for the first Masterclass I ran (June 2024), and I'm so looking forward to sharing the participant's work with you in the coming weeks. In the meantime enjoy Alex Webb's Istanbul. It's a proper treat!!! Be inspired. Be very inspired.

#alexwebb #istanbul #street_photography #weekendworkshops #masterclass #dostreetphotography #weekender #photoweekender #streetphotoworkshop #masteringstreetphotography

caption:
The 3 key skills to master as a street photographer you may not be aware of...

We've all heard about hunting and fishing, working the scene, and observation as the main street photography skills and techniques to master right? 

But there's more to it...

Hitting the streets with an open mind and the right mindset is everything, because being able to capture "the extraordinary in the ordinary" hinges on patience, spontaneity, AND belief!!!

3 key skills to master 

1. You have to be able to wait patiently but also know how long to hang around before ditching a place and moving on.

2. You have to be focussed with a vision and an idea in mind while being open to something random happening.

3. You have to be able to step out of your comfort zone and get up close to your subjects and immerse yourself in the scene (so much so you end up wearing a cloak of invisibility!)

Add these skills to the top 3 elements that take your street photography to the next level, which I wrote about in my last email and on theand you are going to be WINNING!

 >>> https://www.dostreetphotography.com/blog/top-3-elements-street-photography-next-level

caption:
Welcome New Followers!

Photo by me @pollyrusyn. Hello and welcome to the DoSP! This is my irregular ‚ÄúWelcome New Followers‚Äù post. Thank you for stopping by and I hope you stick around. I mostly feature street photography from people who have attended any of my workshops, but there‚Äôs also a monthly hashtag challenge open to everyone, and inspiration posts showcasing the work of famous photographers.

caption:
Learn the elements of what make a great street photo! And have fun doing it.

Join me on a weekend adventure exploring a street-genic city in Europe with a bunch of like-minded photographers.

I'll teach you as much as I can fit in and set you challenging yet achievable street photography assignments. I'll give you the lowdown on how to tackle the assignments depending on your level of experience. You'll also get a sightseeing itinerary, and fun group meals making the whole experience such a sociable, memorable and educational affair!

WHAT YOU LEARN
üì∏  How to set yourself up for success with the right mindset
üì∏  Ways of "working the scene"
üì∏  How to read the street and think like a street photographer
üì∏  How to "make something out of nothing"
üì∏  The keys to ambiguity and mystery
üì∏  Dos and don'ts of framing and cropping
üì∏  Things to look out for to create context and connections
üì∏  How to tell a story (or multiple stories) with a single shot
üì∏  The blueprint for a great photo
üì∏  An introduction to the gestalt principles of visual perception
üì∏  How to approach crowded places in multiple creative ways
üì∏  What to avoid and keep an eye on when shooting
üì∏  Ways to structure your images compositionally
üì∏  And more...

I don't hold anything back, and if you join a Weekender with an event I'll teach you how to shoot events like a street photographer not an event photographer!

üö® What I DON'T do is stand a whole group in one spot and tell you what to photograph. Instead I share ideas, inspiration, tips, and tools so whatever image you capture is all yours. Learning takes trial and error, and getting good takes practice. And all of that leads to a true sense of satisfaction when you nail a shot!

‚û°Ô∏è More intel here: https://www.dostreetphotography.com/street-photo-weekenders

SPECIAL FEATURE: @kackaska‚Äî Winner of the Bologna Weekender 2023. 

Bologna has become one of my favourite cities for street photography. It is so ALIVE with activity. There were so many brilliant shots from this Weekender that it was really difficult to choose an overall winner. But I chose this set from Kat because of the variety of images and the complexity of some of the shots too! Kat is the first second-time winner of a Weekender! :)

So, congratulations to Kat Saradinova for winning "Best of Bologna‚Äù and for producing an excellent series of 9 photos from just one weekend.

I asked Kat who her most inspirational photographers were. Here‚Äôs what she said:

""The street photographers that have inspired me most include:

Alex Webb ‚Äì because‚Ä¶layers. I love to see how he sees.

Vivian Mayer ‚Äì simple, observant, quirky and I love that didn‚Äôt do it for an audience

Martin Martincek ‚Äì this a bit of an odd choice. He will not be known to anyone outside of a very small geographical/time space, and he is not a street photographer as such although people feature in their photographs there is not much actual ‚Äústreet‚Äù there. But his where the first photographs I saw and thought, wow, I‚Äôd love to be able to do a bit of this!"

‚Äî Kat Saradinova

caption:
üì∏üö® Master photography composition by going way beyond the boring old classic composition rules and unlocking the secrets of visual perception.

This self-paced online course will change your photography forever!

As a self-proclaimed geek I have always been fascinated by how things work, including photography. Instead of focusing on the technical side (yawn), I delved into the reasons why some photographs work while others not-so-much.

By studying the work of renowned photographers and researching the Gestalt principles of visual perception (this was a massive rabbit hole!) and applying them to street photography, I was able to hugely improve my own street photography. 

And while street photography may be considered an art, I teach you the science of composition based on how our brains process visual information. You learn how to speak the brain's language and your photography goes to another level. Curious? I know you are!

https://www.dostreetphotography.com/science-street-photography-composition-online-course

caption:
INSPIRATION: SAUL LEITER

Saul Leiter was Born in Pittsburgh in 1923. He  got into art during his late teens but his parents wanted him to follow in his Rabbi father‚Äôs footsteps. He did but dropped out of theology school in 1946 and moved to NYC to pursue his passion for painting. He met Richard Pousette-Dart, an abstract expressionist painter who introduced him to photojournalist W. Eugene Smith who became an important figure in Leiter‚Äôs life. Smith encouraged Leiter to experiment with photography and later introduced him to other influential street photographers, including Robert Frank, William Klein, and Diane Arbus ‚Äî all members of ‚ÄòThe New York School of Photography‚Äô movement. Leiter started out in monochrome, shooting both street photography and portraits, but became an early adopter of colour along with the likes of Ernst Haas, Joel Meyerowitz, William Egglestein, Stephen Shore, and Helen Levitt. And it‚Äôs his colour work that he is best known for. Mostly it was shot in the streets of his Manhattan neighbourhood. And his interest in painting and the abstract came through in his photos shooting through windows, using shadows, curious angles, and often shooting with a telephoto lens creating creative compressions. Often humans where incidental, or faces were obscured. Most of Leiter‚Äôs professional life was as a fashion photographer for magazines such as Elle and Harper‚Äôs Bazaar. At aged 82 he released his book, ‚ÄòEarly Color‚Äô, which was a huge success and led to his first major retrospective and numerous exhibitions worldwide, including his first European exhibition in 2008 at The Foundation Henri Cartier-Bresson in Paris. A film made about Leiter‚Äôs life in 2013, called ‚ÄòIn No Great Hurry‚Äô, received widespread acclaim. Leiter continued to photograph almost up until his death in late 2013, aged 89. His work is kept in permanent collections all over the world‚Ä¶
